Report about breast cancer in Poland

D. Bottoli, P. Dycha, K. Gajewska, A. Gasiorowski
18/05/2016

Dataset description



  • Our dataset consists in observations about the presence of breast cancer in the polish population.

  • There are variables reguarding characteristics of the population as gender, age range, the location detection as TERYT, region, subregion and the amount of new cancer in the respective phases as year, stage 1, stage 2, stage 3, stage 4 and new.

  • Let's have a first look on the relation between the number of cancers, gender, year and age range

Comment #1


  1. This type of cancer is much more present in the females than in the males.
  2. The amount of new cancers detected is approximately constant in the tree years of the analysis.
  3. The distriubutions have a bell shape but we must take into consideration the amount of the population in each of the age range.
    Considering that the curve of the age is decreasing, the proportion of people stricken by the disease is firstly increasing, then constant.

But let's observe deeply in which phase we can find the cancer for the different age range.

FEMALE CANCER STAGES IN 2010

MALE CANCER STAGES IN 2010

Comment #2


  1. The surface of pie-charts doesnt represent the sample size: we wanted only to show the dissimilarity of stages.
  2. This type of cancer is present in a complete different way between the genders. We observe that, while most of the stricken females are in the first/second phase, most of the stricken males are in the fourth phase (the worse one).
    This difference could be traced in the fact that there are no scientific instruments able to recognize the cancer in the firsts phase (for male); furthermore, females must be subjected to periodic analysis for the diagnosis of the possible desease.
  3. The distibutions within the same gender are mostly constant across the age ranges. Its remarkable only the percentage of women 85+ in the lasts two phases.

Comment #3


  1. In the three years, for the different regions, the bell shape of cancers distribution is mantained.
  2. From the chart in the bottom-right corner, we can observe that the detection of new cancers is constant within the regions.
    Of course, the difference in the amount between the regions is caused by the different numerosity of population; thats the reason why, well go deeply to check if there is any region with a greater percentage of cancers.

Comment #4


  • As we can see from this graph, the overall percentage of being stricken by breast cancer is between 0.035% and 0.06%.
  • There are regions where the probability is definitely greater than the average (Lodz, Mazovia, Pomerania, Silesia and West Pomerania); in the region of Supcarpathia the probability is much lower.

  • We analysed here the probability of being stricken by a breast cancer, showing the difference between genders.
  • N.B: the values on the x axis are not in the same scale; for males, probabilities are more than four times lower!
  • We noticed some peaks, but the probabilites are pretty constant along the three years of observations.
